segments.text: Testing 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, testing, testing.
Testing, testing, 1, 2, 3.
This is May the 3rd and I have the pleasure and honor of chatting with
Ricky Wood.
Wood, singular, W-O-O-D.
Yes, W-O-O-D.
This year's Head Yield Leader.
To begin with, Ricky, describe your background, family, where'd you grow up, high school, what do mom and dad do.
Okay.
Tell us about yourself before you came to Texas A&M.
Okay.
I was born in Houston, Texas.
I lived in the same house from the day I was born until
roughly middle of June, summer before my senior year in high school, so roughly 18 years, lived in the same house.
I have an older brother and a younger sister.
My older brother went to the University of Virginia on a full academic scholarship.
My younger sister is a freshman in high school at the moment, and she has aspirations of A&M just simply because of what she's gotten to see through me the last couple years, which is really neat.
I'm excited about that.
I went to the same school.
I went to the Second Baptist School for 14 years, pre-kindergarten all the way through my senior year of high school.
So I went to school with the same – there was about 13 of us that went to school from the day that we started there until we graduated –
Both my parents went to college and they both went to law school.
They both attended undergrad at Rice University, graduated I think in 68 or 69 and then went to University of Texas Law School.
Graduated there in 72.
Moved to Houston, both got jobs in law firms in 1980.
My mom got appointed to be a judge in Houston.
And then in 82, she lost her reelection, ran for something else in 84, and has been a judge ever since.
In Houston, my dad in 1991 got appointed to be a judge in Houston.
And so both my parents are now judges in the Harris County area.
My mom is a state district judge.
My father is a probate judge there in the Houston area.
Why did you attend A&M?
What led you to be interested here?
I came to A&M.
For a couple reasons.
One, I remember my sophomore year, I was very, very involved in football.
I was about 70 pounds bigger than what you see now.
Just because I just worked out a lot and I was just much bigger, just, I mean, bigger in all ways, in all sense of the word.
And so football was what I was going to do.
I was being relatively highly recruited.
Even right, like my sophomore year, places were contacting me to come to their football games and stuff like that.
But my sophomore year during the football season, a friend of mine's older sister was a freshman at A&M.
And so one weekend where we didn't have a football game, he said, do you want to go up to A&M and just stay the weekend and we can go have fun with my sister and all that kind of stuff.
I said, I don't have anything else to do.
So we came.
We came up here.
We went to Midnight Yale practice.
Very similar story that I'm sure you've heard many times.
We went to Midnight Yale practice.
We went back and
We stayed in Mosier Hall when we shouldn't have as sophomores, well I was a sophomore and he was a junior.
In high school we ended up staying in an all girls dorm, which was really fun.
Just being able to live the college life I guess.
You can say we went out somewhere Saturday, we went to a game Saturday night, we went out again.
I was very, very impressed by the close-knit atmosphere here at A&M.
I was very, very impressed by Yale practice, obviously.
That was something where I just said, oh my gosh, this is completely different than anything I've seen.
I mean, my brother was at University of Virginia.
And I had gone up and visited him fall semester of my sophomore year as well.
And it was just very different.
I mean, just very different feels.
Even though there's a lot of similarities between A&M and University of Virginia, there was something that defined A&M as separate.
And I think most of us know what that is.
And so then once my senior year, junior year came around and I started applying to schools, I applied to three schools.
I applied to Dartmouth, Columbia, and then A&M.
I applied to Dartmouth and Columbia to play football.
And I applied to A&M because I was in top 10%.
I had really good ACT scores.
I knew I could get in just not a problem.
And so I applied.
September got my acceptance letter, end of October, and didn't really make the decision to come here until April or so, simply because I realized that this is where I needed to be.
None of the football stuff had panned out, and so I was just like, okay, Lord, I'm just gonna go where you have, where the door's open, and so I came here, and it was, yeah.
Did you go to fish camp?
I did go to fish camp.
Describe it as you would.
It was amazing, actually.
I absolutely loved Fish Camp because I came from such a small high school.
It's not that I wasn't used to dealing with numbers.
I mean, with my parents being involved in what they were, I was always used to being in big groups.
I was always used to having to be at the forefront as far as my personality, having to be forthright in how I speak to people and not waiting for them to speak to me, but me speak to them.
So it's not that I was embarrassed per se, but of course I got there and I was wearing the wrong thing just because it was summer in Texas.
I didn't necessarily bring the right clothes.
I mean it was just one of those things where I didn't really know anyone and so I just came by myself.
I ended up having an amazing time.
My DG leaders were great.
I got back to A&M, went home for four days, packed up, moved up here, and then spent the next three weeks hanging out with my DG group almost every day.
And that was very important in the transition simply because these were people that I hadn't met before and already I felt like I was part of communities.
You're saying DG.
DG in fish camp.
Within each camp that you go to, there's sessions, six sessions.
Within the sessions, there's six camps.
And then within those camps, there's discussion groups, which range from eight to 13 people.
In charge of each discussion group are a male and a female.
So DG, that's what I mean by DG.
Did fish camp have an effect on you and others in terms of spirit, devotion?
Oh, definitely.
Definitely.
As you look back on it now,
How comparatively accurate was Fish Camp in previewing A&M?
Well, it depends on what you're talking about.
If you're talking about campus life, I mean, there's no way.
We're in Lakeview.
We're at a camp.
I mean, it can't really depict.
But as far as the stuff that they gave you just as advice, I think it was very accurate.
The stuff that they tried, I think Fish Camp has a really good way of... And this is why I'm still involved to this day as a co-chair.
It has a very good way of...
keeping the myth of A&M going, if that makes any sense.
Myth might be the wrong word, maybe the aura.

I'm having trouble thinking of the right word, just simply because these freshmen coming here, even those that parents and grandparents and great-grandparents might have come to A&M, they would still not know
what it is really like.
And so they come in, they feel it, they see what it's like.
So then they come to, they start the school year already embedded with those things that, you know, maybe a senior doesn't have anymore simply because they've been here for so long.
But it was a good preparation.
It was an amazing preparation just simply because got there,
got to meet people that had been involved in different stuff.
You weren't supposed to talk about involvements, but it was very obvious that there were.
Presentations were made by people on campus, the Yale Leaders Bonfire, Red Pots, stuff like that, they all came.
It was just, it was really, really neat.
When you came then back to campus to stay, how did you get here, what did you bring, what kind of gear and stuff?
I came
I remember it.
We brought two cars.
I brought my car and then my parents.
And I remember I had a computer, some clothes.
I remember my parents were really big on making sure I was as comfortable as possible.
And so we went to Sam's and bought two $20 bookcases because I stayed in Kane Hall.
My roommate was on the football team for my high school, and so I got to be his roommate in Kane Hall my freshman year, which was really neat.
Moved in, and I remember he had already been there because of two-a-days.
He had been there for a while, and that's why I came up early, because he was really lonely and didn't really have anyone to talk to.
So I came up to hang out with him and moved into the dorm.

I remember Luby's was a favorite place to eat of my family growing up, and so we went to Luby's one last time, and then parking lot of Luby's, Dad shook my hand, Mom kissed me on the cheek and said, have a good time, and then they'd go off.
Did they give you any other advice?
Um, not really, to be honest with you.
Um, they gave me some, just, I mean, just the, I like to think of it in the Hamlet terms of things, be true to yourself, be first to listen, not first to speak, stuff like that.
Just kind of general sentiments on how to live your life, but not necessarily... What about this UVA older brother?
Did he give you any advice or counsel?
Um...

little bit he said make sure and pour into relationships both same-sex and obviously other relationships as far as with women but also said make sure and pour into your same-sex relationships that was his biggest one all right so you're over in Kane Hall did Joel
Was there any kind of ritual or routine or tradition?
Unfortunately, no.

And that's always something that I've looked back that I wish I could have had, that I wish I could have lived in the dorms, maybe on South Side or maybe one on North Side that was much more rich in tradition.
Kane Hall was, it wasn't at all.
Kane Hall was comprised of people

freshmen who wanted a really big dorm and so they got in and they got in early so the so the and i don't want to say intelligence level but the grades and maybe the way in which academics was viewed was a little better of the people that weren't in sports in kane simply because you couldn't get in there unless you applied really early and you got in really early
and athletes, and the athletes just couldn't care anything about A&M necessarily.
I mean, they care about A&M, but they don't care about A&M the same way in which maybe I do or someone else who cares a lot about the spirit and the integrity of the institution.
Where did you eat?
I ate there in King, which was great.
Describe the routine of the dining hall there.
Well, I remember as a freshman, depending on if my roommate was there, I wasn't great friends, especially in the fall, I wasn't great friends with anyone necessarily in my dorm.
And there was really no ways to get

friends within the dorm except maybe if you just hung out in the hallway which I didn't really like but that's just I think that's just the nature of Kane Hall and so right about dinner time you'd walk down there with your ID and there'd be a big long line at the front door and you'd scan it and then you'd go in and you wait in line and I remember seeing all the football players and all the athletes that I knew and all this kind of stuff and I just I remember being just kind of wide-eyed and a total freshman and then I'd get my
get my food and go sit down at the table either by myself or if I recognized a face and I'd go sit down with him and stuff.
But Cain Hall was very hard socially simply because athletes hung out with athletes.
Those that didn't hang out with athletes, they had their own friends.
Maybe he was within the dorm and stuff like that.
And your roommate was an athlete?
My roommate was an athlete, but he was a walk-on athlete.
He was a recruited walk-on, so he wasn't on the same level as...
the highly recruited people.
So how did you make some friends that first semester?
I went out for an organization called Aggie Men's Club.
Now, I don't know if you've heard about it or not, but Aggie Men's Club was an organization started in 1984 by some people who were very upset with the Greek system here on campus.
They thought that it was just dumb and it wasn't fulfilling and it was fake relationships and stuff.
Which I don't, I'm not saying that's the case with all Greek fraternities, but I'm just saying that is the reason that this was made.
And what it is, is it's kind of a
It's it's a selections.
I mean, it's a selectionary group.
And so you know one can't not everybody can get in it.

It's got a It's got a limit of a hundred guys that can be in at a time and you go out you go through selections process and if you get in you get in it's a social service group is essentially what it is really intent on brotherhood really intent on Good true male relationships male friendships.
Where does it meet?
It meets in different places, you know simply because we aren't Greek and
And our dues aren't that much.
We don't have a necessary place to meet every week.
It's kind of whatever room we can find on campus.
We've been meeting in Blocker a lot lately.
Yeah.
Alright, how did you get, how did you get acquainted with Aggie lingo, slang, like you all didn't use dining hall nicknames for food, did you?
No, no we did not.
No, we did not.
But did you, as a freshman, did you start going to Yale practice?
Oh, yes, sir.
I didn't miss a Yale practice my freshman year.
I didn't miss a football game.
Every second, I tried out for fish camp, and I got fish camp counselor.
my freshman year and so right off the bat I was just involved with a group of people that was very A&M oriented.
I was in early session and so there were some people that were in the Corp of Cadets in my fish camp.
There were people in the Corp of Cadets in Aggie Men's Club when I first got in it as a freshman.
So they were people that obviously just integrated me into what it was to be an Aggie.
I went to all that stuff, and I got in.
I had friends that were very involved in other things.

So just hanging around them, going to Southside dorms, going to the Northside dorms, eating in Sabisa with my friends, you just kind of learned it, even though I didn't necessarily experience it firsthand.
I went out to Bonfire.
I worked on Bonfire.
I built Bonfire, stuff like that.
When Bonfire, your freshman year, which would have been the fall of?
About when did you begin work on Bonfire?
First cut.
I went out to the first cut.
When was that?
October 13th.
Okay.
Something like that.
So five or six weeks before.
Yes, five or six weeks.
About how far from the camp?
Where was the first cut?
It was out in Snook.
If you went...
Beyond the river?
Yes, on the other side of the river.
I went out there, and I remember I went with some of my friends.
I went with Aggie Men's Club, and I remember we cut with Dunn Hall.
That's who we went out there with.
What did you used to cut with?

An axe, and then we made our own pot, and we had to make our own pot, and they were... We just went out there with an axe, and I remember we just stayed out there until about 7 o'clock at night and just had an absolutely amazing time.
How long did you work on it?
How long did I work on bonfire or cut that day?
On bonfire?
All that semester.
Oh, okay.
That whole semester.
Did you go out once a day or once a week?
Oh, no, no, no, maybe once a week.
I definitely went to the cuts and then I went to snack maybe once or twice a week.
Do you remember going to your first silver taps?
Yes.
What was it like?
Ominous, honestly.
Much bigger than anything I could have imagined.
I mean, obviously, we got shown it at fish camp.

But it was kind of a reality check, if you want to put it that way, simply because not only was I made aware of what A&M was like and just the ways in which we were set apart just as far as our school, but also...
Oh, I just became very aware of mortality, I guess.
Just because something, especially as an upper teen male, that's something you never think about.
You know, you never think about the consequences of stuff.
And I remember one of the first silver tufts was someone who just got in a car wreck, you know, driving home or something.
And so I just became very aware, I guess, of myself, which was a great learning experience.
All right, now let's go to academics.
What was your major as you arrived?
General studies.
It was general studies.
What did you think you might end up doing professionally in the future?
I didn't know.
You didn't have any clue.
I didn't have any clue.
I had such a wide range of interests.
And it's still that way.
Even though I'm a certain major, that doesn't mean what it is.
I came as a general studies major.
I just took all just the prereq courses.
I knew I didn't want to do engineering.
I remember going to my advisor.
and being like, okay, what classes should I take?
And I was in the honors program when I came in.
And what classes do you want to take?
I said, I don't know.
And she's like, what do you want to do?
I said, oh, gosh, I don't know.
I was just all stressed out as a freshman.
And she was like, well, let's do this.
She was like, do you want to be a doctor?
I said, no.
She was like, do you want to be an engineer?
I said, no.
She's like, well, that takes out two very big things.
And so we know nothing really in science, and we know nothing really in engineering classes.
So that helped out a lot.
So I came in as a general studies major.
And was the advising, as you began, was it good?
Oh, it was wonderful.
Her name was Wanda Watson, and I'll always remember.
I remember I'd go in and speak with her maybe once every two weeks.
Describe your first impressions of going to class at A&M.
First impressions of going to class.
My first class, my first class was a Monday morning.
I remember this perfectly.
My first class was a Monday morning at 910 and it was in Halbooty.
It was geology 101 with a man named Mr. Koenig.
He doesn't work here anymore.
He retired after my freshman year, fall of my freshman year.
And I remember walking in.
It was a big lecture class.
And I remember just being completely
It was really hard simply because I went in there, none of my friends were in there, and so I sat by myself.
And then I remember seeing a big group of core guys walk in.
And then I remember seeing like four guys walk in that had Greek shirts on.
They were wearing their Greek letters.
And I remember just going, wow, I was like they're really involved in something.
And Aggie Men's Club hadn't started at that point.
But I remember thinking to myself, wow, this place is really big.
It was much different than my high school simply because the most people I had in a classroom in high school was 34.
I was sitting here in a 300-person lecture hall that was completely jam-packed.
And I remember him walking in and saying the requirements of the course, and I remember just being like, okay, I guess this is school.
This is college.
I guess this is why we're here.
I remember it was a little overwhelming.
Do you remember what your course load was that first semester?
I took 16 hours.
And what were your personal guidelines for class?
Was it to go to class every day?

I tried to go to class every single day simply because my brother told me this, people had come to A&M, my older friends, they were like, if you go to class, your grade will be a letter grade higher than it would otherwise.
simply because you aren't going to have to study as much, just because you'll have the material presented to you rather than you having to learn about yourself.
Alright, then describe, once you get into the routine, describe a typical class day.
What time did you get up and what did you do when?
One of the requirements of Aggie Men's Club is you have to do interviews with all the actors.
You have to go out and interview them, and then you have a book that you made when you got in.
And they don't take just freshmen.
I think I was one of six freshmen that got in that year.

out for selections that year and so I was one of the only freshmen well one of six freshmen and so pretty much the day would wake up I'd look at my schedule to see if I had an interview that day or not just because you don't miss interviews I mean one thing that I really enjoyed about Aggie Men's Club is that there were definite rules that you had to go by they weren't you couldn't say well today you know what I can't do it you had to do it there were certain things that you had to do and I really enjoyed that about
It gave you discipline that I wouldn't have gotten otherwise, simply because I wasn't only dealing with my schedule, but I had to deal with other people's schedule.
So that taught me a lot right then.
But I'd wake up, check my schedule, maybe 45 minutes before my first class.
I'd shower, go down and get something to eat, walk to class.
I think I had two classes in the morning.
Then I'd go to the 12th Man in the MSC, which is kind of the cafeteria there, because that's where all my friends went to eat.
And so I wouldn't eat in Kane.
I would eat in the 12th Man simply because that's where my friends were.
Aggie Bucks was good.
Aggie Bucks was good, yes, sir.
This was before outbound.
But Aggie Bucks was good.
Aggie Bucks worked.
And so I would go and hang out there.
And then I would go back to my room and my roommate would be there and we'd play Nintendo for a while.
And then I'd go to another class.
I'm chuckling because can you imagine somebody 50 years ago and they'd say, what's that?
Nintendo, excuse me, what's that?
A game, I'd go play video games in my room.
And then depending on if I had anything that week, I would try and read a little bit just to stay up, but it wouldn't necessarily be a priority.
My problem is growing up,
I never had to study very hard.
I'd pick stuff up very fast.
I would always be in trouble in elementary school, and I have to describe this to my girlfriend all the time.
She's like, why were you always in trouble?
And I was like, because I would learn something the first time around.
And so whereas it would take two weeks to teach long division to my classmates, I'd get it on the first day, and then I'd be bored.
And so of course, then I'd just do this.
A little mystic.
I'd just do stuff like this.
Alright, in the afternoon, did you go back to your room to study?
Um, sometimes.
Sometimes I'd go to my room.
Sometimes I would go to something called the browsing library.
I don't know if you've heard about that.
That was really neat simply because you got to listen to music.
I'm a multitasker.
I can't sit in a quiet room and study.
I have to have other stuff going on.

So whether I was going to study, maybe go to a coffee shop like Sweet E. Jeans or Barnes & Noble or something like that where there would be other stuff that while I was studying would kind of drown out some of my thoughts, I guess, because that's the thing that keeps me from studying the most.
All right, then the evening meal where probably?
during weeknights, where would you?
It really depended.
Usually I'd go over to Southside or Northside and hang out with my friends that lived in the dorms.
Or sometimes, I remember I got a girlfriend beginning of, right in the middle of my freshman year, right in the middle of the fall of my freshman year.

So I spent a lot of time over at her dorm, spent a lot of time hanging out with her friends and my friends, going off campus, going to houses, going to Bible studies, going to praise and worship sessions, going to parties, stuff like that.
During that first semester, how did you and your family back home, how did you stay in contact with parents?
Um, calling cards.
Okay.
Did you write any letters?
Um, no.
Well, I mean every once in a while we'd write a letter.
Um, and every once in a while we'd write an email.
This was right when email was becoming the thing.
Um, this was right before it.
And cell phones still, obviously no one had cell phones at this point.
Um, but...
Didn't really write letters.
Calling was a big part of it.
I mean, we'd call.
Obviously, we had an answering machine.
I'd get home, and my mom would be like, well, how are you?
How are things going?
And so I'd call them back, and we'd just talk for a little bit then.
All right.
And that first, say, mid-semester, as you first got tests back, how did things go?
They went well, honestly.
The classes that I were involved in were...
stuff in which it kind of built off what I had already learned.
My memory is such that if I learn something, I'm going to keep it with me, and so my geology class was really just like my eighth-grader science class.
So I really didn't have to study for that that much, which was really exciting to me simply because my first semester wasn't one that just came in and my head just got blown off me.
It was one in which it was just kind of a, I guess, an interim process, a learning process to what college studying would be like, but the classes weren't all that extremely difficult.
And how did you, what did you wear to class?
How did you dress?
It depended, honestly.
At the very beginning I dressed nice, but then by the end of the semester I was wearing pajama pants and t-shirts and I was rollerblading to class and stuff like that.
And so it kind of depended on what was going on after class.
And did you get a haircut regularly?
No, not my first semester freshman year.
I did not.
It just kind of went.
It was never this long.
But for me, my head was buzzed all throughout high school.
And so, I remember letting it grow.
And you went to all the football games.
What other campus activities did you get involved in early?
Campus activities.

um bonfire and bonfire silver taps uh and the aggie now what's the aggie men's club does it have a place a formal place to meet um no it doesn't like we don't have a house or anything i mean obviously we'd have meeting i had a meeting once a week so that's something i'd get involved in a lot we would have then we would have prayer meetings that of course i would go to um
My fish camp would still hang out a lot, and so I'd do some of that.
But as far as campus activities, there wasn't a campus ritual or anything.
There isn't near the stuff I have now.
We've gotten to the point where now, once a week, it's stuff that we go do.
There's always stuff to be done on every day.
During that freshman first semester, did you make some friends that you now look back on as dear friends?
Yes, most definitely.
Oh, yeah.
There's friendships that I made that first semester that I'm going to have for the rest of my life.
Without a doubt.
And did you make any long excursions anywhere during that?
Actually, yes, I did.
Maybe not the first semester, but spring break, my friend and I, we were just like, well, what are we going to do?
We don't know what we're going to do for spring break.
So we drove from here to Virginia and stayed with my brother for spring break.
I mean, big time road trip.
It was awesome.
A whole lot of fun.
At the university.
you were on the grounds.
You're aware that you don't refer to that as a campus.
Oh, of course not.
It's the grounds.
And you don't ask.
And I was visiting my fourth year, my first year brother.
And you don't ask someone what class they were in.
When were you on the grounds?
When were you on the grounds?
Oh, sure.
Oh yeah, they got their own stuff going there, which was neat.
It was so much fun.
Trivia for you.
Southern history is my thing, and I was doing research there about 40 years ago.
They were restoring the room on the west lawn where Edgar Allan Poe was living when they suspended him for what we today call substance abuse.
They opened up with a grand opening and all this.
Someone had written in red drippy paint,
inside the word never more.
Somebody had slipped in.
That's great.
And only there.
Financially, were you on tight funding or?
I got an allowance, and so that was relatively tight funding.
Probably not the same as someone who's putting their way through college.
It was tight for me.
I mean, I was living on about $150 a month, which wasn't, I mean, that's a lot of money, don't get me wrong, but when you take into account going out to eat, I'm so sorry.
No way.
Going out to eat and stuff like that.
Where did, that first semester, where did you go, if you were really going to have a special meal, where would you go?
Cafe XL.
Cafe XL, okay.
Yeah, that was the one where everybody talked about.
That's where you go for a good meal.
And then if you and your buddies were going to have a big time on Friday or Saturday night, where would you go?
Freebirds.
Honestly, Freebirds, I ate at Freebirds a whole lot.
I didn't go out as far as drinking or stuff like that a lot my freshman year simply because
One, I was young.
I couldn't do it simply because of age and simply because of my parents.
Breaking the law wasn't something that I did very easily simply because of the way in which I was raised.
And so I didn't do a lot of that.
Yeah, I just go out to free birds and we go to the house.
In the years you've been here, how often have you observed Aggie, underage Aggies, deliberately violating the laws about alcohol?
A lot.
A lot.
Oh yeah, ever since my freshman year.
There was a lot more than just alcohol down in Kane Hall.
I remember after football games people would just walk in with kegs and just put them right there in the hallway.
And your guess, would Kane Hall be worse at that than other dorms?
Yes, simply because they don't follow the same regulations as, let's say, RHA.
They answer the athletic department.
I was vice president of Kane Hall my freshman year.
And so I'd go to RHA meetings, and they really didn't even look at us as a dorm on campus, simply because we didn't do the same things they did.
The same rules didn't apply to us, simply because Kane was athletic.
Now, I'm assuming that Kane Hall didn't have the good bull pranks that the core dorms had.
No, they didn't, unfortunately.
Was it a quiet place?
No, it wasn't a quiet place.
It was loud for different, the athletes were very loud.
Obviously they never studied, they partied a whole lot.
So every night of the week, I remember the hallway that I lived on.
The first four rooms down here was all non-athletes.
The next four rooms down there were all athletes.
And that side of the hallway always had smoke coming out of the rooms.
It was definitely the party place.
And my floor was too.
